bib_record.title: Reaction mechanism of the O-16 + d reactions.

free_txt: In order to obtain the absolute normalization for the
charged particle reactions, the elastic scattering of
2.0 MeV protons was measured used the same target as
was used in the case of the 6.00 MeV angular
distribution.
The target had a uniform concentration of oxygen to a
depth corresponding to an energy loss of about 230
keV for 5.00 MeV deuterons. Beyond this depth, the
concentration of oxygen decreased rapidly.
Corrections for the detector efficiency, dead time in
the detection system, and for neutron scattered in the
target backing were applied, and the spectra were
normalized using the count in a monitor detector.
No explanation of relative units is given.

the estimated uncertainties in: the total amount of
oxygen in the target, the stopping power of molybdenum
and oxygen, neutron detector efficiency, background
subtraction, and charge collection as well as
statistical uncertainties in peak area determinations.
The thin target consisted of a layer of tantalum oxide
(Ta2O5) deposited on a tantalum foil 0.08 cm thick.
Data from text p.2238
Four solid state detectors suspended from a
movable support allowed data to be collected
simultaneously at four angles. A fifth solid state
detector was held fixed at 90 degr. to the beam
direction for use as a monitor during measurement of
the angular distributions and as a fifth detector
during the measurement of the yield curves.
The total uncertainty in the absolute
normalization was estimated to be 10% due to possible
systematic errors arising from target nonuniformity,
charge collection, and uncertainty as to the chemical
nature of the target. Of this total approximately 5%
was due to statistical errors in the data.

The targets consisted entirely of calcium hydroxide
[Ca(OH)2], produced by the rapid reaction of calcium
oxide (CaO) with air borne moisture. The angular
distributions were measured with targets in which the
48Ca enrichment was 87%. The target was estimated to be
about 3 keV thick.
